Compute the product $\dfrac 43\cdot \dfrac 64\cdot \dfrac 85\cdot \dfrac{10}{6}\cdot \dfrac{12}{7}\cdot \dfrac{14}{8}$.
inference:
$\dfrac 43\cdot \dfrac 64\cdot \dfrac 85\cdot \dfrac{10}{6}\cdot \dfrac{12}{7}\cdot \dfrac{14}{8} = \dfrac{4}{3} \cdot \dfrac{6}{4} \cdot \dfrac{8}{5} \cdot \dfrac{10}{6} \cdot \dfrac{12}{7} \cdot \dfrac{14}{8}$

We can cancel common factors from the numerator and denominator.
$= \dfrac{4}{3} \cdot \dfrac{6}{4} \cdot \dfrac{8}{5} \cdot \dfrac{10}{6} \cdot \dfrac{12}{7} \cdot \dfrac{14}{8} = \dfrac{4}{3} \cdot \dfrac{\cancel{6}^3}{\cancel{4}^1} \cdot \dfrac{\cancel{8}^2}{\cancel{5}} \cdot \dfrac{\cancel{10}^5}{\cancel{6}^3} \cdot \dfrac{\cancel{12}^2}{7} \cdot \dfrac{\cancel{14}^7}{\cancel{8}^2}$
$= \dfrac{4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 5 \cdot 2 \cdot 7}{3 \cdot 1 \cdot 5 \cdot 3 \cdot 7 \cdot 2 \cdot 2}$
The common factors in the numerator and denominator can be canceled out.

$= \dfrac{4 \cdot \cancel{3} \cdot 2 \cdot 5 \cdot \cancel{2} \cdot \cancel{7}}{\cancel{3} \cdot 1 \cdot 5 \cdot \cancel{3} \cdot \cancel{7} \cdot 2 \cdot \cancel{2}}$
$= \dfrac{4 \cdot 2 \cdot 5}{5 \cdot 1 \cdot 2 \cdot 2} = \dfrac{40}{20}$
$= 2$

Final Answer: $\boxed{2}$ I hope it is correct.
ground_truth:
We can write
\[\frac{4}{3} \cdot \frac{6}{4} \cdot \frac{8}{5} \cdot \frac{10}{6} \cdot \frac{12}{7} \cdot \frac{14}{8} = \frac{4 \cdot 6 \cdot 8 \cdot 10 \cdot 12 \cdot 14}{3 \cdot 4 \cdot 5 \cdot 6 \cdot 7 \cdot 8}.\]Then
\[\frac{6}{3} = \frac{8}{4} = \frac{10}{5} = \frac{12}{6} = \frac{14}{7} = 2,\]so the expression becomes
\[\frac{4 \cdot 2^5}{8} = 2^4 = \boxed{16}.\]
